1️⃣ Foreign Key (Connecting Tables)
Simple Idea

A Foreign Key is a column that links one table to another.

👉 It creates a relationship between tables

Mental Model 🧠

Think:

Primary Key → Identity of a table
Foreign Key → Reference to another table
Real-World Example
Table 1: Students
id (PK)	name
1	Akshay
2	Rahul
Table 2: Courses
course_id (PK)	course
101	CSE
102	ECE
Table 3: Enrollments
id	student_id (FK)	course_id (FK)
1	1	101
2	2	102

👉 Here:

student_id refers to Students.id

course_id refers to Courses.course_id

This is Foreign Key

Python Connection 🧠
students = [
 {"id":1,"name":"Akshay"},
 {"id":2,"name":"Rahul"}
]

courses = [
 {"course_id":101,"course":"CSE"},
 {"course_id":102,"course":"ECE"}
]

enrollments = [
 {"id":1,"student_id":1,"course_id":101},
 {"id":2,"student_id":2,"course_id":102}
]

👉 Here:

student_id connects to students

course_id connects to courses

Same as Foreign Key in database

Why Foreign Key is Important

✔ Connects tables
✔ Avoids data duplication
✔ Maintains consistency

Example:
Instead of writing "Akshay" everywhere → use id

SQL Example
CREATE TABLE enrollments (
 id INT PRIMARY KEY,
 student_id INT,
 course_id INT,
 FOREIGN KEY (student_id) REFERENCES students(id),
 FOREIGN KEY (course_id) REFERENCES courses(course_id)
);
Memory Trick
Foreign Key = Bridge between tables
2️⃣ Normalization (Making Data Clean)
Simple Idea

Normalization means organizing data to:

Remove duplicates

Avoid redundancy

Improve efficiency

Problem Without Normalization ❌

Imagine this table:

student	course	instructor
Akshay	CSE	John
Akshay	AI	John
Rahul	ECE	Mike

👉 Problems:

"Akshay" repeated

"John" repeated

Waste of memory

Hard to update

Solution: Normalize ✅

Split into multiple tables:

Students
id	name
1	Akshay
2	Rahul
Courses
id	course	instructor
101	CSE	John
102	AI	John
103	ECE	Mike
Enrollments
id	student_id	course_id
1	1	101
2	1	102
3	2	103

👉 Now:

No repetition

Clean structure

Easy updates

Python Connection 🧠
Bad Design ❌
data = [
 {"name":"Akshay","course":"CSE","teacher":"John"},
 {"name":"Akshay","course":"AI","teacher":"John"}
]
Good Design ✅
students = [{"id":1,"name":"Akshay"}]

courses = [
 {"id":101,"course":"CSE","teacher":"John"},
 {"id":102,"course":"AI","teacher":"John"}
]

enrollments = [
 {"student_id":1,"course_id":101},
 {"student_id":1,"course_id":102}
]
Why Normalization Works

Because it:

✔ Reduces duplication
✔ Saves memory
✔ Makes updates easy
✔ Improves data consistency

Simple Memory Trick
Normalization = Break big messy table into smaller clean tables
